<div class="sect2">
<h3 id="510">3.6. Applying the Reverse charge procedure</h3>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>The <strong>Reverse charge procedure in accordance with article 194 of the VAT Directive</strong> is a special VAT tax regulation. Is the procedure applied, the recipients (= your customers) are liable for VAT and not the merchant or company providing the service (= you as a merchant or your company). The reverse charge procedure is only applicable to B2B deliveries. If it is applied, it is necessary that</p>
</div>
<div class="ulist">
<ul>
<li>
<p>the VAT ID of the customer is added in the order.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>a net invoice is issued for this customer.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>a note stating that the reverse charge procedure is applied is displayed on this net invoice.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This setting is dependent on location, which means that you can decide separately for each location if the procedure is to be applied. The Reverse charge procedure is by default deactivated, i.e. <strong>No</strong> is selected for every location. If you want to activate this option, go to the <strong>Setup » Client » [Select client] » Locations » [Select location] » Accounting » Tab: Basic settings</strong> menu and select <strong>Yes</strong> from the drop-down list. Take the explanation in <a href="#table-reverse-charge-procedure">Table 4</a> into consideration.</p>
</div>
